**Explanation:** Option d is the correct answer. Article 26 of the Constitution of India is a fundamental right that grants the freedom to manage religious affairs to every religious denomination or any section thereof.
It provides that subject to public order, morality and health, every religious denomination or any section thereof shall have the right:
- to establish and maintain institutions for religious and charitable purposes;
- to manage its own affairs in the matter of religion;
- to own and acquire movable and immovable property; and-to administer such property in accordance with law National security, education, and secularism are not mentioned in Article 26 as grounds for limiting the religious rights of any denomination or section.

**Explanation:** Option d is the correct answer. Article 19(1) of the Constitution of India includes the rights:
- (a) to freedom of speech and expression;
- (b) to assemble peaceably and without arms;
- (c) to form associations or unions;
- (d) to move freely throughout the territory of India;
- (e) to reside and settle in any part of the territory of India; and
- (f) omitted
- (g) to practise any profession, or to carry on any occupation, trade or business **Important Tips** Reasonable restrictions by the state in India include:
- Freedom of speech and expression can be restricted for reasons such as national security, public order, defamation, and incitement to offense.
- Restrictions on the freedom of assembly can be imposed to maintain public order and protect the integrity of the nation.
- Freedom of association can be limited to ensure public order, national integrity, and morality.
- The freedom of movement and residence can be restricted in the interest of public welfare and protection of marginalized groups.
- Certain professions involving immoral or dangerous activities may face restrictions to maintain social order and public safety.

